    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>Shopping and Shipping</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Patrick Shaw responds to Michelle Slatalla's May 25 article on free shipping from Internet merchants; says there is now a need to question size of boxes used to ship such items</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thank you for the Online Shopper column about free shipping from Internet merchants. Now you should address the issue of the size of the boxes that things come in. For example, a book arrives surrounded by bubble wrap on all four sides. A bar of soap comes in a big box stuffed the same way.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Thank you for the Online Shopper column about free shipping from Internet merchants. Now you should address the issue of the size of the boxes that things come in. For example, a book arrives surrounded by bubble wrap on all four sides. A bar of soap comes in a big box stuffed the same way.</p>
        <p>What is the relationship of cost to size, or is it only weight that counts? Think of all the space that could be saved if the boxes were smaller. Not to mention the waste of paper or cardboard and all the stuffing and tape.</p>
        <p>PATRICK SHAW  Chicago</p>
        <p>INCOMING</p>
      </block>
